  "text": "The total bacterial population at different GIT regions was estimated with q PCR analysis by measuring the total copy number of bacterial 16S rRNA genes. It is known that bacteria can possess multiple copies of 16S rRNA which may lead to an overestimation of population data [CITATION_1] . No region and sample type effect was observed on the total bacterial population in ingestaand mucosa-associated communities of 3-week old calves (Table 5) , except a significant sample type effect was observed for cecum (P = 0.01). However, both GIT region and sample type had a significant impact on bacterial density of 6-month old calves (Table 5 ). Higher mucosa-associated bacterial numbers were observed in the rumen (P = 0.05) and higher ingesta-associated bacterial numbers in the rumen, cecum, and colon (P = 0.03) of 6-month old calves (Table 5) .",
